{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1948090801/0348.xml":{"full_text":"THE NOME- NUGG ET\nPublished Monday. Wednesday and Friday by The\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\nNome, Alaska\nTelephone: Main 125 P. O. Box 618\nSI.50 PER MONTH $16.00 A YEAR\nEntered as second class matter October 14. 1943. at the postoffiet\nat Nome, Alaska, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nWednesday, September 8, 1948\nSITKA TAX PLAN SUCCESS\n(Anchorage Daily Times)\nA city sales tax has met with considerable success in\nSitka( Mayor Waino Edward Hendrickson, mayor of\nJuneau, said recently while visiting in Anchorage.\n\u201cMore than $9000 has been collected by the town in\nthe first two months after the tax was enacted,\u201d Hen\ndrickson said. \u201cThe city expects to raise $50,000 a year\nfrom the levy,\u201d he pointed out.\nHendrickson declared a similar action is being con\nsidered at Ketchikan. Revenues from the one cent tax\nat Sitka are earmarked for use by the school and hos\npital.\n\u201cUnder the plan transient workers pay their share\ntoo,\u201d the visiting mayor said.\nFEAR OF DEFLATION\n(Christian Science Monitor)\ni\n\u201cThey are really more concerned about deflation\nthan about inflation.\u201d Senator Taft\u2019s \u201cthey\u201d referred to\nthe Truman Administration. And despite the Presi\ndent\u2019s pleas for legislation to curb inflation, there is a\ngood deal of truth in Mr. Taft\u2019s statement. For the Ad\nministration could do much more to check inflation if it\nwere not afraid of deflation.\nBut if the spokesman for Republicans in Congress\nhad been making a non-partisan statement he would\nhave had to make his \u201cthey\u201d much more inclusive.'Act\nually, it covers a big part of the community and defin\nitely includes the Republican party. Nealy everybody\nprefers the boom to even a \u201cstabilizing recession.\u201d\nNearly everybody is afraid that measures to check in\nflation will start deflation. Producers like high prices;\nworkers like high wages. Nobody wants to pull out a\ngirder that could possibly send the whole economy\ncrashing.\nIn fact, both major parties are more inclined to insert\ngirders. Mr. Taft charged that every time farm prices\nshow any sign of falling, the Democrats rush to support\nthem. He might have added that the Republicans sel\ndom get left behind.\nIn fact, the 80th Congress, controlled by Republicans,\nis responsible for continuing the most indefensible sub\nsidy for inflated food prices\u2014that on potatoes. Former\nsecretary of agriculture Anderson urged that this war\ntime measure be dropped. It has cost the taxpayers\n$170,000,000 and is now adding $4,000,000 a week. It\nhas caused the dumping of millions of bushels (the\ncheapest form of surplus disposal) and costly expedi\nents to avoid dumping. But Congress insisted on keep\ning the subsidy on the 1948 crop.\n\u201cThey are really more concerned about deflation,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Taft.\nFRAYING THE CORD\n(The Denver Post)\nThe Soviet decision to withdraw consular repressen\ntatives from the United States and to close the Ameri\ncan consulate in Vladivostok is simply another fraying\nof the slender cord that binds Soviet-American rela\ntions. In fact the closure of our consulate in Vladivos\ntok will make little difference. Our representatives\nhave not been allowed to move, freely there; they have\nbeen confined and watched as all Americans are in the\nSoviet Union.Our trade with Russia is negligible now,\nas are the interests of American nationals in the Soviet\nUnion.\nOn the other hand, the Russians have much to lose.\nHANGING IN THE BALANCE\n'oV cs/\nWhen they remove their consulates from New York and\nSan Francisco, they take away valuable posts. The Sov\niet government voluntarily narrows its control over\nRussian nationals in this country\u2014few as they are. In\nthe future, they will have more difficulty when they\nwant to force the return of Soviet citizens who would\nrather live elsewhere.\nObviously the Soviets took this action in an attempt\nto retrieve prestige, after their representatives failed to\nenforce extraterritoriality on American soil. Perhaps\nanother school teacher episode will cause the breaking\nof diplomatic relations between the Soviet Union and\nthe United States. Certainly, at least, this incident\nshows how little the Russians value the maintenance of\ncordial relations with this country.\nIf they insist on following this course, if they demand\nextraterritorial privileges and are so miffed they they\nretaliate when those demands are rejected, they bring\nabout eventual disruption of all diplomatic relations.\nBARROOM \u201cUNIFICATION\u201d\n(By Lawrence Martin)\nMore than a year after the legal unification of the\narmed forces of the United States, Defense Secretary\nForrestal has found it necessary to demand \u201cintegra\ntion\u201d of the army, navy and air force operations, an in\ntegration that Americans had a right to expect at the\ntime of unification.\nSecretary Forrestal and the chiefs of the three serv\nices have had to call upon high-ranking officers to stop\ninterservice rivalry and observe the spirit as well as\nthe letter of the Newport decisions regarding functions\nof the services.\nAt this time defense is a vital factor. Nearly 80 per\ncent of the American budget is being spent in direct\nconnection with national security. Apparently, how\never, many army, navy and air force officers have not\nyet accepted the unification of our defense forces; in\nstead, they prefer to think of national defense in terms\nof their own organizations.\nAs far as we can see, individual or service glory\nhunting at this time can do nothing but weaken out en\ntire program of national defense. There is no place for\npetty jealousy in the armed forces, as Secretary Forres\ntal made quite clear. If the present leaders of the serv\nices are not pliable enough to place the interests of the\nnation above those of their individual service, it is ob\nvious that new leaders must be found.\nUp to date there is scanjt evidence that unification\nhas been more than a name on a barrom floor*.\n\u201cWorld revolution and world domination are avow\ned aims of the Russian Communists. Those cannot be\nachieved by peaceful methods. Violence is the method\nadvocated. There is no escape from the logic of Dulles\u2019\n[warning that \u2018the Soviet regime isnot a regime of\n1 peace, and does not purport to be\u2019.\u201d\u2014Bruce Gustin.\n0\nAlaska Highway\nGood But Needs\n0\nImprovement\n(By Vern Haugland)\n<(/P) Special Washington Service'\nWASHINGTON (A?)\u2014The Alas\nka Highway is in good shape ex\ncept for the southern approach in\nCanada, assistant secretary of the\ninterior William E. Warne said.\nIf properly developed, Warne\ntold a reporter, the famous war\nbuilt highway may channel a\ntourist trade of $80,000,000 to\n$200,000,000 yearly into Alaska.\n\u201cBut there are two or three\nsections along the 550-mile strfp\nin northern Alberta, between Ed\nmonton and Dawson Creek, that\nare pretty bad,\u201d Warne said.\nThe interior section, unim\nproved dirt road that becomes\ngreasy when it rains, totals only\nabout 125 miles.\n\u201cErnest C. Maihing, Alberta\nPremier, told me the province\nplans to put the road in shape\u2014\nrelocating some sections and grav\neling them as rapidly as possible.\n\u201cWe hope to pursue the prob\nlem of surface improvements\nwith Canadian officials this year.\u201d\nWarne drove over the road from\nFairbanks to Edmonton, with H.\nRex Lee, interior\u2019s assistant direc\ntor of territories, Kenneth Kadow\ndepartment field representative\nand Col. John Noyey, chief of\nroads in Alaska.\nFrom Fairbanks to Dawson\nCreek it is a well-engineered,\nhigh class, gravel-surface road\nequally well maintained in Alas\nka and in Yukon Territory and\nBritish Columbia, Warne said.\nHe added that the highway\nneeds:\n1. Additional roadside facilities,\nespecially in Alaska. Canada, he\nsaid, is far ahead of Alaska in\nproviding overnight facilities.\n2. Cafes and gasoline stations.\nAlacka has started to black-top\nthe first 90 miles of the road out\nof Fairbanks and plans a similar\nsurface to the Canadian border.\n\u201cIt will be necessary to hard\nsurface the road all the way be\nfore it will become a major tourist\nroute,\u201d Warne said.\n\u201cThe Alaska highway already\nhas had a major influence on\nAlaska and it is destined to be\nmuch more important in the fu\nture. It would be a great sharrie\nnot to use this fine road as it\nshould be used.\u201d\nWarne said development of the\nhighway should particularly be\nboosted by the cities most likely\nto benefit from tourist develop\nment Fairbanks, Anchorage,\nWhite Horse, Dawson Creek, Ed-\nmonton, Lethbridge, Calgary, and\nGreat Falls and Cut Bank., Mont.\n0\nVANCOUVER, B. C., </P)\u2014'The\nBritish Columbia government will\nhave to spend another five million\ndollars on the Hart Highway from\nPrince George to Dawson dreek,\nthe Vancouver News-Herald re\nported thise week.\nThe route, which would cut\n1,000 miles off the highway dis\ntance to Alaska from the west\ncoast, was expected to cost six\nmillion when work started in\n1945. It was to be ready for use,\nlinking the Caribo Route and the\nAlaska Military Highway, this\nyear.\n\u201cNow it is far in the future,\u201d\nthe article said, quoting the pre\nmier as saying the government\nstill was determined to put the\nroad through.","height":"27028","width":"19908"}}
